'''''I Want My Phone Back''''' is an American [[game show]] [[Web television|web television series]] that premiered on November 2, 2016 on Comcast Watchable. In 2017, it was subsequently picked up by [[Facebook Watch]] where it has since aired two seasons.

The series was created by Luke Kelly-Clyne and is hosted by Alana Johnston. The show's team of improvisers include Blake Rosier, Inessa Frantowski, Brandon Gardner, Laci Mosely, Kausar Mohammed, and Oscar Montoya.

==Premise==
''I Want My Phone Back'' follows host "Alana Johnston and a cast of improv performers take to the streets of Los Angeles, giving passersby the chance to win up to $1,000 — by handing over their mobile phones and letting the show’s pranksters post to social media, and text and call their contacts. The longer contestants stay in the game, the more money they make."<ref name="ComcastOrder">{{cite web|last1=Spangler|first1=Todd|title=Comcast’s Watchable Unveils First Original Series, Including Show With Vine Star Logan Paul|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/comcast-watchable-logan-paul-original-series-1201841193/|website=Variety|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=August 23, 2016}}</ref>

==Production==
===Development===
The series originated as a short video entitled ''I Want My Phone Back: The Scariest Game Show Ever'' that was produced by Big Breakfast for [[CollegeHumor]] and initially released on [[YouTube]] on November 13, 2015. The short was created by Luke Kelly-Clyne, directed by Todd G. Bieber, and featured Brandon Gardner as host.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 'I Want My Phone Back' Game|url=http://www.tastefullyoffensive.com/2015/11/the-i-want-my-phone-back-game.html|website=Tastefully Offensive|date=November 13, 2015|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I Want My Phone Back: The Scariest Game Show Ever|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=12&v=SaKVvBsMa54|website=YouTube|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Collegehumor's I Want My Phone Back: The Scariest Game Show Ever|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5200028/?ref_=ttfc_fc_tt|website=IMDb|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=November 13, 2015}}</ref>

The video proved to be quite successful on CollegeHumor's YouTube channel where it quickly earned a million views. After testing how the idea could be turned into a 30-minute TV show or 10-minute web series, the series was sold to streaming service Comcast Watchable.<ref name="AdExchanger">{{cite web|last1=Sluis|first1=Sarah|title=How CollegeHumor Created A Successful Facebook Watch Show - AdExchanger|url=https://adexchanger.com/ad-exchange-news/collegehumor-created-successful-facebook-watch-show/|website=AdExchanger|accessdate=January 13, 2018|date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>

On August 22, 2016, it was announced that the short had been developed into a series and that Comcast Watchable had ordered a first season consisting of ten episodes.<ref name="ComcastOrder"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Weiss|first1=Geoff|title=Comcast’s Watchable Platform Premieres Exclusive Shows From Refinery29, Mitú, and Cut.com - Tubefilter|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/08/22/comcasts-watchable-platform-exclusive-shows-refinery29-mitu-cut/|website=Tubefilter|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hamedy|first1=Saba|title=New series from WatchCut, mitú, Refinery29 headed to Comcast's Watchable|url=http://mashable.com/2016/08/23/comcast-watchable-new-series-mitu/#V80gHzmdMEq0|website=Mashable|date=August 23, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Megh|title=Here’s an Episode of CollegeHumor’s New Game Show ‘I Want My Phone Back’|url=http://splitsider.com/2016/12/heres-an-episode-of-collegehumors-new-game-show-i-want-my-phone-back/|website=Splitsider|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=December 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gutelle|first1=Sam|title=Contestants Shout "I Want My Phone Back" In New Episodes Of CollegeHumor’s Game Show - Tubefilter|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/12/06/i-want-my-phone-back-college-humor-watchable/|website=Tubefilter|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> It premiered on November 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title="I Want My Phone Back" on Watchable|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/7041257/i-want-my-phone-back-on-watchable|website=College Humor|accessdate=January 8, 2018|date=November 1, 2016}}</ref>

In September 2017, it was reported that Comcast was reassessing their Watchable platform and planning to de-emphasize over-the-top distribution, and halt future work centered on Watchable originals including ''I Want My Phone Back''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baumgartner|first1=Jeff|title=Comcast Sees New Path Ahead for ‘Watchable’ {{!}} Broadcasting & Cable|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/platforms/comcast-sees-new-path-ahead-watchable/168852|website=Broadcasting Cable|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Patel|first1=Sahil|title=Comcast puts its OTT play Watchable on life support - Digiday|url=https://digiday.com/media/comcasts-watchable-is-no-longer-funding-original-content-may-shut-down-soon-sources-say/|website=Digiday|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref>

===Move to Facebook Watch===
In mid-2017, it was announced that the series had been picked up for two new seasons by [[Facebook Watch]]. The first of those ten episode seasons premiered on August 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ehrenkranz|first1=Melanie|title=Finally, a Place to Watch Viral Garbage on the Internet|url=https://gizmodo.com/finally-a-place-to-watch-viral-garbage-on-the-internet-1800679386|website=Gizmodo|date=September 6, 2017|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gutelle|first1=Sam|title=CollegeHumor's 'How To Spot' Brings Nature Show Satire To Facebook Watch - Tubefilter|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/11/13/college-humor-how-to-spot-facebook-watch/|website=Tubefilter|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=November 13, 2017}}</ref>

